Valkenburg, Limburg, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Goswin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old English personal name <i>Godwine</i>, derived from <i>god</i> ‘god’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’. This was borne in the 11th century by the Earl of Wessex, the most important man in England after the king. He was an influential adviser to successive kings of England, and father of the  King Harold  who was defeated at Hastings in  1066 . The personal name continued in use after the Norman Conquest long enough to give rise to a surname. Modern use as a given name is probably a transferred use of the surname, rather than a revival of the Old English name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Goswin I. von Heinsberg-Valkenburg was born in 1060, in Wassenberg, Heinsberg, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, his father, Dietrich von Wassenberg, was 25 and his mother, Hedwig von Montaigu, was 19. He married Oda von Walbeck in 1087. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 1 April 1128, in Valkenburg, Limburg, Netherlands, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1060–1 APR 1128":"1060–1. aprill 1128","1060–1128":"1060–1128","1060–1129":"1060–1129","1070–1152":"1070–1152","1088–1129":"1088–1129","1102–1168":"1102–1168","1035–1082":"1035–1082","1042–Female":"1042–Surnud","1088":"1088","1042":"1042","1152":"1152","1060":"1060","1082":"1082","1070":"1070","1 APR 1128":"1. aprill 1128